<DOC><DOCNO> AP890919-0066 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0738EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Secord     09-19 0176</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Secord,170</SECOND><HEAD>Iran-Contra Defendant Fined, Driver's License Suspended</HEAD><DATELINE>VIENNA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord, akey figure in the Iran-Contra affair, has been convicted for thesecond time since May of driving while intoxicated.   Secord was sentenced in General District Court on Monday to a$500 fine, with $250 suspended, and loss of his driver's license forsix months, according to Vienna town prosecutor Kevin Kessler.   Kessler said Secord failed a field sobriety test after hisvehicle was seen in June approaching, at about 2 miles an hour, anintersection with a green light and being passed by other vehicles.   Secord is awaiting trial on a charge of refusing to give a bloodor breath sample, the prosecutor said.   In the earlier conviction, which is under appeal, Secord wasfined $300 and ordered to join an alcohol safety program.   Secord, an arms dealer, was the chief operative for former MarineLt. Col. Oliver North in the Iran-Contra affair in the diversion ofIranian arms-sales profits to U.S.-backed rebels in Nicaragua.</TEXT></DOC>